A '''vacuum-lift''',<ref name="SW 20">[[Star Wars (1977) 20|''Star Wars'' (1977) 20]]</ref> also known as '''vacuum tube'''<ref name="Hint Book">''[[Star Wars Hint Book]]''</ref>, is a chute that allowed rapid travel to great heights.<ref name="Hint Book">''[[Star Wars Hint Book]]''</ref> Air pressure in the tube carried an individual entering it to a higher level. The variety of places Vacuum Tubes were used include [[Hangar|docking bays]], [[Jawa/Legends|Jawa]] [[Sandcrawler/Legends|sandcrawlers]], and the [[DS-1 Orbital Battle Station/Legends|first Death Star]].<ref name="SWNES">[[Star Wars (1991 video game)|''Star Wars'' video game (1991)]]</ref>

==Behind the scenes==
In ''[[Adventures of the Starkiller, Episode I: The Star Wars]]'', the second draft of the first [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'']] movie, the concept of a '''vacuum elevator''' (also called vacuum tube in the draft), was featured when referring to the elevators in the [[DS-1 Orbital Battle Station/Legends|''Death Star'']].<ref name="Draft">''[[Adventures of the Starkiller, Episode I: The Star Wars]]''</ref> Vacuum-lifts went on to also be part of the ''Star Wars'' universe, through their introduction in [[Star Wars (1977) 20|''Star Wars'' (1977) 20]],<ref name="SW 20" /> and [[Star Wars (1991 video game)|''Star Wars'' (1991 video game)]].<ref name="SWNES" />

A guide to the [[1991]] [[Star Wars (1991 video game)|''Star Wars'' video game]] in ''Nintendo Power'' magazine referred to these devices as "'''Jump Boosters'''."<ref name="NP">{{StoryCite|story=Star Wars (article)|book=Wikipedia:Nintendo Power|bformatted=''Nintendo Power'' Vol. 28|sformatted=''Star Wars''}}</ref>

